{{Infobox protected area | name = Los Kat√≠os National Natural Park | alt_name = PNN Los Kat√≠os | iucn_category = II | map = Colombia |relief=1 | map_caption = Location of Los Kat√≠os in Colombia | location = [[Antioquia Department|Antioquia]] & [[Choc√≥ Department|Choc√≥]], {{flag|Colombia}} | nearest_city = | embedded1 = {{designation list | embed=yes | designation1 = WHS | designation1_date = 1994 <small>(18th [[World Heritage Committee|session]])</small> | designation1_type = Natural | designation1_criteria = ix, x | designation1_number = [http://whc.unesco.org/en/list/711 711] | designation1_free1name = State Party | designation1_free1value = [[Colombia]] | designation1_free2name = Region | designation1_free2value = [[List of World Heritage Sites in the Americas|Latin America and the Caribbean]] | designation1_free3name = [[List of World Heritage in Danger|Endangered]] | designation1_free3value = 2009‚Äì2015<ref>[http://whc.unesco.org/en/news/1306/ Colombia‚Äôs Los Kat√≠os National Park removed from List of Heritage in Danger] at [[UNESCO]] website</ref> }} | coordinates = {{coord|7|40|0|N|77|00|0|W|format=dms|display=inline,title}} | area = {{convert|720|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}} | established = August 6, 1974 | visitation_num = | visitation_year = | governing_body = [[National System of Protected Areas (Colombia)|SINAP]] }} [[File:Giant anteater (4531346746).jpg|thumb|The Giant Anteater, one of the inhabitants of Los Kat√≠os.]] '''Los Kat√≠os National Natural Park''' ({{lang-es|Parque Nacional Natural (PNN) Los Kat√≠os}}) is a protected area located in northwest [[Colombia]] which covers about {{convert|720|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}}. The elevation ranges between {{convert|50|and|600|m|ft|abbr=on}}. It is a part of the [[Dari√©n Gap]], a densely forested area shared by [[Panama]] and Colombia, and is contiguous with the [[Dari√©n National Park]] in Panama. The [[Pan-American Highway]], when completed as proposed, would pass near or through Los Kat√≠os. The park was declared a [[World Heritage Site]] in 1994 due to the extraordinary diversity of plant and animal species represented. The park contains over 25% of the bird species reported for Colombia in an area less than 1% of the total Colombian territory.
The topography of the Los Katios National Park is diverse, with low hills, forests and wet plains comprising its total area.<ref name="Los Kat√≠os National Park">{{cite web|title=Los Kat√≠os National Park|url=http://whc.unesco.org/en/list/711|publisher=UNESCO World Heritage Centre|accessdate=15 March 2013}}</ref>
The two largest parts of the park are the [[Serran√≠a del Dari√©n]] mountains, which lie to the west, and the [[Atrato River]] floodplains in the east. The floodplains hold exceptionally fertile soil and consist of alluvial plains of two types. One consists of low-lying terraces that flood often and the other has high terraces that seldom flood. There are also low hills of up to {{convert|250|m|ft}} in elevation and others that are {{convert|600|m|ft}} high. Swampy marshes spread for nearly half of the park's total area. The wetlands of the Atrato floodplain are unique. Cativo, one of the indigenous species, can grow to a height of {{convert|50|m|ft}}. It lends its name to a formation called 'catival', something that is found nowhere in the world except Colombia, south Central America and [[Jamaica]].<ref name="Los Kat√≠os National Park"/>
