The production and distribution of [[pornographic film]]s are both activities that are lawful in many, but by no means all, countries so long as the [[pornography]] features performers aged [[Age of majority|above a certain age]], usually eighteen years. Further restrictions are often placed on such material.

== Africa ==

=== Botswana ===
The possession of "Indecent and obscene material such as pornographic books, magazines, films, videos, DVDs and software" is prohibited in [[Botswana]]. Possession or import of such material is illegal and punishable by a fine or up to 4 years' imprisonment.<ref>[http://www.botswanatourism.co.bw/getting_in/entry_requirements.html Botswana Tourism Board], "Entry Requirements". botswanatourism.co.bw. Retrieved 15 December 2008. {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090129154753/http://www.botswanatourism.co.bw/getting_in/entry_requirements.html |date=29 January 2009}}</ref>

=== Egypt ===
In [[Egypt]], it is illegal to distribute pornography.<ref>{{cite news|title=Egyptian MP sends porn to fellow parliamentarians over WhatsApp, blames 'hackers'|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/egyptian-mp-sends-porn-fellow-parliamentarians-over-whatsapp-blames-hackers-1567718|publisher=International Business Times|date=27 June 2016|accessdate=1 July 2016}}</ref> The possession and import of pornography are offences.<ref>{{cite web|title=A Court in Egypt Declares Internet Pornography Illegal|publisher=ValueWalk|author=Paul Shea|date=28 March 2012|accessdate=16 July 2017|url=http://www.valuewalk.com/2012/03/a-court-in-egypt-declares-internet-pornography-illegal/}}</ref> Unlike numerous African nations which have no laws against child pornography, [[Internet in Egypt|Egypt blocks child pornography websites]] and dealing in child pornography carries a minimum sentence of five years and fines of US$29,000.<ref>{{cite book|title=Pornography and The Criminal Justice System|author=Carmen M. Cusack|publisher=CRC Press|date=2014|ISBN=9781482260021|page=248|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=GZXSBQAAQBAJ}}</ref> In 2009 Egypt's Administrative Court ruled that internet pornography should be banned, describing it as "venomous and vile". In 2012 the country's Prosecutor General ordered government ministries to block the websites,<ref name=RT>{{cite news|title=Egypt bans online porn, causing split in society|url=https://www.rt.com/news/egypt-pornography-society-ban-204/|publisher=RT News|date=7 November 2012|accessdate=1 July 2016}}</ref> and the Administrative Court repeated its order for the Cabinet to block pornographic websites in 2015.<ref name=Cole/> However, the cost of blocking large numbers of pornographic websites has prevented the full implementation of the court's ruling.<ref name=RT/> Egypt has the highest viewing figures for pornography in the [[Middle East]] according to a survey of access to [[Pornhub]].<ref name=Cole>{{cite news|title='Everyone should be free to watch porn films': Actress faces jail in Egypt for inciting immorality after urging the country's unmarried men to view explicit films 'to cool down'|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-3310127/Actress-faces-jail-Egypt-inciting-immorality-urging-country-s-unmarried-men-use-porn-cool-down.html|author=Brendan Cole|newspaper=Daily Mail|date=9 November 2015|accessdate=1 July 2016}}</ref>

=== Ethiopia ===
All forms of pornography is illegal in Ethiopia, its production in that country is rare. The legal status of Internet pornography in Ethiopia is uncertain.{{citation needed|date=September 2018}}

=== Morocco ===
In 2004, Morocco introduced severe punishment for promoting pornography.<ref>{{cite book|title=Countries at the Crossroads: A Survey of Democratic Governance|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ebjEVjJ-DcAC|first1=Sanja|last1=Tatic|first2=Christopher|last2=Walker|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|year=2006|isbn=9780742558014|page=365}}</ref> Producing pornography of any kind is illegal in Morocco. However, it does not apply much on Internet pornography; porn websites are widely accessible in Morocco.{{citation needed|date=July 2018}}

=== Nigeria ===
Nigeria has no national laws prohibiting pornography, although the public display of graphic sexual material is illegal in Lagos. The country has a small indigenous pornography industry which produces exclusively heterosexual pornography as [[LGBT rights in Nigeria|homosexual activity in Nigeria is illegal]]. Some Muslim politicians in the national government have proposed a nationwide block on pornographic websites.<ref>{{cite web|title=Nigeria's Porn Industry Is Getting Ready To Overtake America's|url=http://www.konbini.com/ng/lifestyle/nigeria-is-home-to-the-newest-porn-economy/|website=Konbini|author=Odunayo Eweniyi|date=18 September 2017}}</ref> There is significant piracy of pornography in Nigeria, with pirated pornographic DVDs being sold from roadside stalls in [[Lagos]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Criminology: The Core|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wzGSWLTPguAC|first=Larry J.|last=Siegel|publisher=Cengage Learning|year=2010|isbn=9780495809838|page=364}}</ref> Pornography is also sold in Nigerian [[sex shop]]s and some [[pornographic magazine]]s are produced in the country, often reproducing pictures from foreign magazines. The first officially acknowledged [[hardcore pornography|hardcore pornographic]] film produced in Nigeria was ''Better Lover Valentine Sex Party''. It was not submitted to the National Film and Video Censors Board for classification and it was immediately banned on the grounds of obscenity and immorality.<ref>{{cite book|title=Global Perspectives on Social Issues: Pornography|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gCwR-WxI0x0C|first1=Richard|last1=Procida|first2=Rita James|last2=Simon|publisher=Lexington Books|year=2007|isbn=9780739120927|page=93}}</ref> Internet pornography is widely viewed in Nigeria. In 2015 the monthly average for the number of searches for pornography was 135,000, and in December 2014 and 2015 the proportion of searches for pornography (relative to other searches) was higher in Nigeria than in the United States. In 2013 Nigeria ranked second globally for Internet searches for [[gay pornography]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Nigeria, We‚Äôve Got A Sexuality Problem!|url=http://subomiplumptre.com/porn/|author=Subomi Plumptre|date=13 October 2015}}</ref>

=== South Africa ===
Pornography rated X18 is permitted by the law only if sold to persons over the age of 18 in registered stores. It is an offense to host a pornographic web site in South Africa because of the difficulty of age-verification and the requirement that pornography only be distributed from designated, licensed physical premises. It is also unlawful to visually represent bestiality (also rated XX), but not in text descriptions. Supplying violent pornography is an offence in any form, but the law allows the production of pornography that is not prohibited.

Distribution of pornography is regulated by the Films and Publications Act of 1996<ref>{{cite newspaper|title=Government Gazette|url=http://www.gov.za/sites/www.gov.za/files/Act65of1996.pdf|publisher=Republic of South Africa|date=8 November 1996}}</ref> which is enforced by the Films and Publications Board.<ref>{{cite web|title=Film Classification Query Engine|publisher=Films and Publication Board|url=http://www.fpb.gov.za/home_page.asp|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090103025901/http://www.fpb.gov.za/home_page.asp |archive-date=3 January 2009 }}</ref>

=== Sudan ===
Pornography is prohibited in Sudan and the laws are strict. Pornographic websites are blocked by the government, pornography is largely inaccessible, and porn possession, production, distribution and sale can lead to fines, prison or [[corporal punishment]].{{citation needed|date=November 2018}}

=== Uganda ===
Pornographic DVDs have in the past been sold on the streets in [[Uganda]].<ref name=Fallon>{{cite news|title=Confusion over Uganda's 'miniskirt ban' leads to public attacks on women|url=https://www.theguardian.com/fashion/fashion-blog/2014/feb/28/uganda-miniskirt-ban-attacks-women|author=Amy Fallon|date=28 February 2014|newspaper=The Guardian|accessdate=30 June 2016}}</ref> However, an Anti-Pornography Act (popularly known as the "Anti-Miniskirt Law") was signed into law in 2014 with the stated objectives of defining what constitutes the offence of pornography and establishing a Pornography Control Committee.<ref>{{cite book|title=Women and Girls Rising: Progress and Resistance Around the World|editor1=Ellen Chesler|editor2=Terry McGovern|publisher=Routledge|date=2015|ISBN=9781317482666|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=ZJrwCQAAQBAJ|page=149}}</ref> The Committee is responsible for the implementation of the law and for taking measures to detect, prohibit, collect and destroy pornographic materials.<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Museveni Signs Anti-Pornography Bill into Law|url=http://www.redpepper.co.ug/museveni-signs-anti-pornography-bill-into-law/|magazine=Red Pepper|accessdate=30 June 2016}}</ref> The law broadly defines pornography as "any representation of the sexual parts of a person for primarily sexual excitement".<ref name=Fallon/> The law says that "a person shall not produce, traffic in, publish, broadcast, procure, import, export, sell or abet any form of pornography". Breaches of the law are punishable with up to ten years in jail.<ref>{{cite web|title=Uganda‚Äôs anti-pornography law targets media more than miniskirts|url=http://www.journalism.co.za/blog/ugandas-anti-pornography-law-targets-media-more-than-miniskirts/|date=9 Mar 2014|author=Raymond Mpubani|website=Wits Journalism|accessdate=30 June 2016}}</ref> Prior to the passing of the act there were a number of laws concerning aspects of pornography in Uganda, but this was the first law to create a specific offence of pornography.<ref>{{cite web|title=Parliament passes Anti-Pornography Law|url=http://www.parliament.go.ug/new/index.php/about-parliament/parliamentary-news/325-parliament-passes-anti-pornography-law|publisher=Parliament of the Republic of Uganda|accessdate=30 June 2016}}</ref> The law repeals and replaces Section 166 of the Penal Code Act, widening the legal interpretation of pornography and prohibiting it comprehensively.<ref>{{cite news|title=Uganda bans miniskirts, pornography|url=http://www.newvision.co.ug/new_vision/news/1337826/uganda-bans-miniskirts-pornography|newspaper=New Vision|date=18 February 2014|accessdate=30 June 2016}}</ref> The law has been subject to challenge in the Constitutional Court on the basis of its vague wording and the broad powers of the committee.<ref>{{cite web|title=Anti-Pornography Act - Human Rights Activists And Civil Society Organisations Challenge The Legality Of The Act In Constitutional Court - Uganda|url=http://www.sihanet.org/news/anti-pornography-act-human-rights-activists-and-civil-society-organisations-challenge-legality|publisher=Strategic Initiative for Women in the Horn of Africa|date=2015|accessdate=30 June 2016}}</ref> In 2015 Ugandan pop singer [[Jemimah Kansiime]] was charged under the law for appearing in a music video.<ref>{{cite news|title=Uganda performer faces 10-year jail sentence under new anti-porn law|url=http://en.rfi.fr/africa/20150525-uganda-performer-faces-10-year-jail-sentence-under-new-anti-porn-law|date=25 May 2015|author=Michel Arseneault|publisher=Radio France International|accessdate=30 June 2016}}</ref>

== Asia ==
{{Main|Pornography in Asia}}

=== Bangladesh ===
{{main|Pornography in Bangladesh}}
By passing "Pornography Control Act, 2012" Bangladesh government has prohibited carrying, exchanging, using, selling, marketing, distributing, preserving, filming etc. of pornography (Sexually explicit materials, unless it has artistic and/or educational value). Penalties include a maximum of 10 years in prison and fines up to Tk.500,000/(USD 6,410). Most of the pornographic websites are blocked by the government.<ref>{{cite news|author1= |title=Anti-Pornography Law in Bangladesh Lawyers Bangladesh |url=http://lawyersbangladesh.com/?p=324 |date=3 January 2012}}</ref>

=== China ===
{{Main|Pornography in China}}
It is illegal to sell or distribute pornography in China, but it is not illegal to own or to watch it. Google, Yahoo, YouTube and other websites do not allow users in China to perform searches related to sex.{{citation needed|date=April 2018}} Pornographic material in China comes from Hong Kong, Macau, Taiwan, or Japan.{{citation needed|date=December 2017}}

==== Hong Kong ====
Hong Kong is the primary source of Chinese-language erotica.{{citation needed|date=January 2016}}

Pornographic films in Hong Kong are referred to as [[List of Hong Kong Category III films|Category III films]], after the territory's motion picture rating system. Category III films would generally be considered softcore by American and Japanese standards, often featuring more elaborate and comical plots than foreign equivalents. In the early 21st century many of the roles involving sex scenes are actually performed by Japanese actresses, with any dialogue dubbed into Chinese, rather than by Chinese women.

Hardcore pornographic videos and films, in both physical and digital forms, can be legally sold in the territory.

=== India ===
{{Main|Pornography in India}}
The possession and viewing of pornography by an adult in a private residence is legal in India. In July 2015 the [[Supreme Court of India]] ruled against the blocking of pornographic websites.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://m.hindustantimes.com/india/it-s-legal-to-watch-porn-in-the-privacy-of-your-house-says-sc/story-WSre0BXJDfHbErouNgmdtK.html|title=It's legal to watch porn in the privacy of your house, says SC|date=2015-07-09|newspaper=Hindustan Times|access-date=2016-12-20}}</ref> In August 2015 the [[Government of India]] issued an order to Indian ISPs to block at least 857 websites that it considered pornographic<ref>{{cite newspaper|newspaper=Deccan Chronicle|url=https://www.deccanchronicle.com/150803/nation-current-affairs/article/porn-ban-complete-list-857-porn-websites-blocked-india|title=Banned: Complete list of 857 porn websites blocked in India|date=4 August 2015|access-date=11 July 2018}}</ref> but the order was quickly lifted following widespread objections.<ref>{{cite news|title=India lifts porn ban after widespread outrage|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-33783539|date=5 August 2015|work=BBC News|access-date=11 July 2018}}</ref> Child pornography in electronic form is illegal in India under section 67B of the [[Information Technology Act, 2000]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Central Government Act: Section 67 [B] in The Information Technology Act, 2000|url=https://indiankanoon.org/doc/176300164/|website=Indian Kanoon|access-date=11 July 2018}}</ref> and in February 2016 the Supreme Court asked the Indian Government to suggest ways of banning all forms of child pornography.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.deccanchronicle.com/technology/in-other-news/270216/supreme-court-asks-centre-to-suggest-measures-to-ban-child-pornography.html|title=SC asks Centre to suggest measures to ban child pornography|date=2016-02-27|newspaper=Deccan Chronicle|access-date=2016-12-20}}</ref> The making and distribution of pornography is illegal in India.<ref>{{cite book |last=Rajak|first=Brajesh|title=Pornography Laws: XXX Must not be Tolerated. In order to curb this Jio has blocked around 827 pornographic sites in Oct 2018.|origyear=2011|edition=Paperback|year=2011|publisher=Universal Law Co. |location=Delhi|isbn=978-81-7534-999-5|page=61}}</ref>

=== Japan ===
{{Main article|Pornography in Japan}}
Pornography is legal in Japan; however, there are restrictions. [[Pubic hair]] and [[Sex organ|genitalia]] must be pixelated or censored and all participants must 18 years of age or older.

=== Lebanon ===
Pornography in Lebanon is illegal and is subject to several legal provisions, but it's considered legal to access pornographic websites for personal use only.{{citation needed|date=September 2018}}

=== North Korea ===
{{Main article|Pornography in North Korea}}
Both domestic and imported works of [[pornography]] have been available in [[North Korea]] since recent decades.<ref name="Shin2015">{{Cite web | title = Pornography in North Korea | last = Shin | first = Junsik | work = New Focus International | date = 13 April 2015 | accessdate = 20 September 2016 | url = http://newfocusintl.com/pornography-in-north-korea/| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150417152313/http://newfocusintl.com/pornography-in-north-korea/| dead-url = yes| archive-date = 17 April 2015}}</ref> Producing, distributing, importing and watching pornography is prohibited.<ref name="HassigOh2015">{{cite book|last1=Hassig|first1=Ralph|author2=Kongdan Oh|title=The Hidden People of North Korea: Everyday Life in the Hermit Kingdom|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7T19CAAAQBAJ&pg=PA106|edition=2nd|date= 2015|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield Publishers|location=Lanham|isbn=978-1-4422-3719-3|page=106}}</ref>

Possession of pornography became widespread among elites during the late 1990s. Political and army elites are the most active consumers of pornography. Locally produced pornography initially appeared during the reign of [[Kim Jong-il]]. A typical North Korean-made [[pornographic film]] involves nude or scantily clad women dancing with music.<ref name="Moon2007">{{Cite web | title = Porno Became Widespread in '90s, Thanks to the Dear Leader | author = Moon Sung Hwee | work = Daily NK | date = 23 December 2007 | accessdate = 21 September 2016 | url = http://www.dailynk.com/english/read.php?cataId=nk01300&num=3042}}</ref>

Importing pornography to North Korea is harshly punished. Pornography is sold openly on the [[China‚ÄìNorth Korea border]] regardless of regulations.<ref name="Schwartzman2009">{{Cite web | title = Is There Porn in North Korea? | last = Schwartzman | first = Nathan  | work = Asian Correspondent | date = 27 November 2009 | accessdate = 20 September 2016 | url = https://asiancorrespondent.com/2009/11/is-there-porn-in-north-korea/}}</ref> Despite attempts to curtail circulation of imported pornography, most of the pornography watched in North Korea is currently made abroad.<ref name="Moon2007"/> A significant part of pornographic media in circulation consists of Chinese [[bootleg recording]]s of poor quality.<ref name="Shin2015"/>

There is [[Censorship in North Korea|no access]] to foreign pornographic websites from within North Korea.<ref>{{Cite web | title = North Korea now blocking Facebook, Twitter, other websites | agency=Associated Press  | work = The Big Story | date = 1 April 2016 | first=Eric |last =Talmadge| accessdate = 21 September 2016 | url = http://bigstory.ap.org/article/128ede4fc729447ab4540a7438ce0175/north-korea-now-blocking-facebook-twitter-other-websites-0}}</ref>

North Korea has ratified the [[Optional Protocol on the Sale of Children, Child Prostitution and Child Pornography]] of the [[Convention on the Rights of the Child]].<ref>{{Cite web | title = North Korea | author =  | work = Human Rights Watch | date =  | accessdate = 21 September 2016 | url = https://www.hrw.org/world-report/2016/country-chapters/north-korea}}</ref> However, there are currently no specific laws to combat [[child pornography]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://www.icmec.org/wp-content/uploads/2016/02/Child-Pornography-Model-Law-8th-Ed-Final-linked.pdf#45|page=34|title=Child Pornography: Model Legislation & Global Review|edition=8th|date=2016|publisher=International Centre for Missing & Exploited Children|access-date=8 December 2016}}</ref>

=== South Korea ===
{{Further information|Internet censorship in South Korea}}
Pornography is banned by the government in South Korea, with laws strictly enforced. The distribution, sale or display of obscene materials via the Internet can be punished with up to two years' imprisonment, although there is no penalty for watching or possessing Internet pornography. The exception is child pornography, the possession of which carries a maximum one-year prison sentence, and the maximum sentence for distributing, selling or displaying it for commercial purposes is ten years. Many foreign pornographic websites are blocked, and those found to be operating from within the country are shut down.<ref>{{cite news|author1=Hyung-Jin Kim|title=South Korea's porn fight 'like shoveling in a blizzard'|url=http://sys03-public.nbcnews.com/technology/south-koreas-porn-fight-shoveling-blizzard-1C7511844|accessdate=1 August 2014|publisher=NBC News|agency=Associated Press|date=10 December 2010|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20140806004953/http://sys03-public.nbcnews.com/technology/south-koreas-porn-fight-shoveling-blizzard-1C7511844|archivedate=6 August 2014|df=}}</ref> The Korea Internet Safety Commission is responsible for instructing [[Internet service provider]]s to block access to "pornography and nudity".<ref>{{Cite journal|title=Comparing Online Activities in China and South Korea: The Internet and the Political Regime|first=Jongpil|last=Chung|journal=[[Asian Survey]]|volume=48|number=5|date=September‚ÄìOctober 2008|pages=727‚Äì751|doi=10.1525/as.2008.48.5.727}}</ref> [[Google Search]] in South Korea filters search results for around 700 terms considered by the government to be adult in nature unless the user demonstrates that they are aged over 19.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://searchengineland.com/searching-for-an-adult-topic-youll-have-to-prove-your-age-to-google-korea-11246|title=Searching For An Adult Topic? You'll Have To Prove Your Age To Google Korea|website=Search Engine Land|date=17 May 2007|access-date=7 November 2017}}</ref>

===Pakistan===
{{See also|Pornography in Pakistan}}
Pornography in Pakistan is illegal and is subject to several legal provisions. The Government has put a 100% ban on internet website containing such material since November 2011. The list of banned pornographic websites is updated on an ongoing basis.

===Philippines===
{{See also|Pornography in the Philippines}}
The Philippine penal code prohibits the production and distribution of obscene publications. There is a ban on pornography, but the law enforcement is relaxed and doesn't enforce the prohibition. Pornographic movies are available on [[Television in the Philippines|Philippine cable television]]. Since 2014 there was a little local production.{{citation needed|date=November 2017}}

Some ISPs in the Philippines have blocked access to pornographic websites since January 2017, due to the Republic Act 9775 or the Anti-Child Pornography Law.

=== Saudi Arabia ===
Items considered pornographic by Saudi Arabian standards are forbidden in the country. Customs authorities enforce strict regulations concerning the importation of pornographic items into Saudi Arabia. Such items may be confiscated on arrival and the owner may be subject to a fine.<ref>{{cite book|title=Americans Traveling Abroad: What You Should Know Before You Go|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dLnhH1ImoaMC|first=Gladson I.|last=Nwanna|publisher=Frontline Publishers, Inc.|year=2004|isbn=9781890605100|edition=3rd|page=267}}</ref> Accessing pornographic websites can lead to imprisonment, fine, deportation or any other severe punishment by the government.{{citation needed|date=September 2017}}

=== Syria ===
Pornography in Syria is illegal and is subject to several legal provisions. The Syrian government began blocking pornography sites in late 2017.{{citation needed|date=September 2018}}

===Turkmenistan===
{{Main article|Pornography in Turkmenistan}}
Even though the legal status of pornography in Turkmenistan is unknown, a law, passed on 1 January 2015, banning citizens to access pornography on the internet<ref>[http://www.15min.lt/naujiena/aktualu/pasaulis/turkmenijoje-uzdrausta-internete-izeidineti-prezidenta-ir-ziureti-pornografija-57-475592 Turkmƒónijoje u≈ædrausta internete ƒØ≈æeidinƒóti prezidentƒÖ ir ≈æi≈´rƒóti pornografijƒÖ]</ref> suggests that pornography may be illegal in Turkmenistan.

== Europe ==
{{Main|Pornography in Europe}}
European hardcore pornography is dominated by a few pan-European producers and distributors, the most notable of which is the [[Private Media Group]]. Most European countries also have local pornography producers, from Portugal (''Naturalvideo'') to Romania (''Floyd-Agency''), all of which compete with larger, international organizations with varying levels of success.

Many U.S.-based pornography websites distribute European pornography as a [[genre]]. These actresses (often advertised as "Eurobabes")<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.eurobabeindex.com | title=Eurobabeindex | accessdate=2006-10-05}}</ref> may conform more to a look usually seen in U.S. actresses than European ones, although they may still be considered to look "more natural". European pornography typically de-emphasizes [[breast implant]]s, among other aesthetic factors.

=== Belarus ===
Production, dissemination and assembly of pornography is banned, with laws strictly enforced. Breaking the law is punishable with up to four years in prison.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sk.gov.by/ru/news-ru/view/razmeschenie-pornografii-v-sotsialnyx-setjax-vlechet-ugolovnuju-otvetstvennost-1323/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160320024054/http://sk.gov.by/ru/news-ru/view/razmeschenie-pornografii-v-sotsialnyx-setjax-vlechet-ugolovnuju-otvetstvennost-1323/|dead-url=yes|archive-date=20 March 2016|title=–†–∞–∑–º–µ—â–µ–Ω–∏–µ –ø–æ—Ä–Ω–æ–≥—Ä–∞—Ñ–∏–∏ –≤ —Å–æ—Ü–∏–∞–ª—å–Ω—ã—Ö —Å–µ—Ç—è—Ö –≤–ª–µ—á–µ—Ç —É–≥–æ–ª–æ–≤–Ω—É—é –æ—Ç–≤–µ—Ç—Å—Ç–≤–µ–Ω–Ω–æ—Å—Ç—å|author=|date=24 June 2016|work=sk.gov.by|accessdate=8 November 2016}}</ref>

=== France ===
In France, pornography is overall permitted, but with distinctions: 
* Hardcore pornography must not be sold to minors under the age of 18.
* Softcore porn is allowed for people 16 and over. 
* Extremely violent or graphic pornography is considered [[X rating|X-rated]], and so may be shown only in specific theaters, and may not be displayed to [[minor (law)|minors]].
* Some pornography has a special ([[value-added tax]]) VAT: a 33% tax is levied on X-rated movies, and a 50% excise is placed on pornographic online services.

The ratings system has caused controversy; e.g., in 2000 the sexually explicit and violent film ''[[Baise-moi]]'' was initially rated only as "restricted" by the French government. This classification was overturned by a ''[[Conseil d'√âtat (France)|Conseil d'√âtat]]'' ruling in a lawsuit brought by associations supporting [[Christianity|Christian]] and [[family values]].

Some movies are forbidden to minors under 18, without the X rating, like ''[[Baise-moi]]'', ''[[Ken Park]]'' or ''[[Saw III|Saw 3]]'', so that these movies can be viewed in theaters and not attract VAT.

=== Germany ===
The constitution and law are very strict about [[hardcore pornography]], especially when compared to very liberal laws about [[softcore pornography]], [[prostitution]] and [[sex shop]]s. Supplying hardcore pornography to people who are less than 18 years old is an offence, and shops selling it must keep people under the age of 18 from entering their premises. If only a part of the shop is dedicated to pornography, it must be completely closed off from the rest of the premises. Alternatively, shops may choose not to display their goods or advertise that they sell them, in which case minors may be admitted. Websites hosting pornographic material within Germany must comply with very strict rules about verifying that viewers are over 18.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heise.de/newsticker/BGH-reicht-Check-der-Ausweisnummer-als-Zugangshuerde-fuer-Online-Pornos-nicht-aus--/meldung/97651|title=BGH reicht Check der Ausweisnummer als Zugangsh√ºrde f√ºr Online-Pornos nicht aus|first=Stefan|last=Krempl|date=19 October 2007|work=heise.de|accessdate=31 August 2016}}</ref>

Soft porn is less restricted, and may even be broadcast on TV at night. The age threshold is usually FSK-16. In contrast many uncut action films or video games easily reach the FSK-18 rating.

=== Hungary ===
{{Main|Pornography in Hungary}}
In Hungary, pornography is unlawful if sold or shown to children under 18 years of age. Displaying the genitals openly, as on the cover of a magazine, is not prohibited.

=== Iceland ===
The production or sale of pornography is prohibited in Iceland. Heavy fines were applied in 2001 and ten years earlier a fine was applied to the first manager of the first private TV-station (and the only case to present) in Iceland for showing the Danish "mainstream" [[Zodiac-films]], ''[[I Tvillingernes tegn]]'' and ''[[I Tyrens tegn]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.visindavefur.is/svar.php?id=2677| title=Hva√∞ er kl√°m? |accessdate=31 August 2015 |language=is}}</ref> In early 2013 there was a draft proposal by [[√ñgmundur J√≥nasson]], the [[Minister of the Interior (Iceland)|Minister of the Interior]], to extend the ban to online pornography to protect children from violent sexual imagery.<ref>{{cite news | last = Associated Press | author-link = Associated Press | title = Iceland seeks internet pornography ban | url = https://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/feb/25/iceland-seeks-internet-pornography-ban | work = [[The Guardian]] | publisher = [[Guardian Media Group]] | date = 25 February 2013 }}</ref> The plan has been stalled since the change in government during the [[Icelandic parliamentary election, 2013|parliamentary election on 27 April 2013]]. Since then, there have been no changes to the relevant legislation, and no changes have been formally proposed.<ref>{{cite web | last = Staff writer | title = Iceland: Key developments: June 2014-May 2015, limits on content | url = https://freedomhouse.org/report/freedom-net/2015/iceland | website = freedomhouse.org | publisher = [[Freedom House]] | date = 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last = Helgad√≥ttir | first = √Åsta Gu√∞r√∫n | author-link = √Åsta Helgad√≥ttir | title = The Icelandic initiative for pornography censorship | journal = [[Porn Studies]] | volume = 1 | issue = 3 | pages = 285‚Äì298 | publisher = [[Taylor and Francis]] | doi = 10.1080/23268743.2014.928462 | date = July 2014 | url = https://dx.doi.org/10.1080/23268743.2014.928462 | ref = harv | postscript = .}}</ref>

=== Italy ===
{{Main|Pornography in Italy}}
In Italy, it is illegal to distribute pictorial or video pornography to persons under the age of 18. However, persons over 18 years of age are permitted to view pornographic material.

=== Russia ===
According to Russian law, consumption of pornography is allowed though the production of it is not. The illegal production, distribution, and "public demonstration" of pornography is punishable by a 2- to 6-year prison term. [[Federal Service for Supervision of Communications, Information Technology and Mass Media|Roskomnadzor]], the Russian government's media overseer, has the power to order the blocking of pornographic websites. In 2015 the agency required the blocking of the Russian-language version of [[Pornhub]] and 10 other pornographic sites on the basis of a court ruling.<ref>{{cite news|title=Russia Blocks Access to Popular Porn Sites|url=http://www.tol.org/client/article/26316-russia-pornhub-roskomnadzor-blacklist-media.html|date=15 September 2016|work=Transitions Online|accessdate=16 November 2016}}</ref>

There is nevertheless some uncertainty concerning the legal status of pornography in Russia. The law criminalizes only the 'illegal' production and selling of pornography (which implies that it sometimes can be legal), but two circumstances make enforcement of the law difficult: (1) the lack of a legal definition of pornography, and (2) no law defining when production or selling is permitted.{{Citation needed|date=April 2011}}

=== Ukraine ===
Pornographic production, distribution, broadcasting (both audio and video), transportation, import and advertisement is forbidden by law in Ukraine.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://zakon4.rada.gov.ua/laws/show/1296-15|title=–ó–∞–∫–æ–Ω –£–∫—Ä–∞—ó–Ω–∏ "–ü—Ä–æ –∑–∞—Ö–∏—Å—Ç —Å—É—Å–ø—ñ–ª—å–Ω–æ—ó –º–æ—Ä–∞–ª—ñ"|date=5 March 2015|publisher=Verkhovna Rada of Ukraine|language=Ukrainian|accessdate=5 March 2015}}</ref>

=== United Kingdom ===
{{main|Pornography in the United Kingdom}}
In [[England and Wales]], the main legislation on pornographic materials is the [[Obscene Publications Act 1959]], the [[Obscene Publications Act 1964]], and the [[Indecent Displays (Control) Act 1981]]. Video-oriented depictions of hardcore material (with certain exceptions for works considered primarily 'artistic' rather than pornographic) were banned until 1999, when the removal of trade barriers with other [[European Union]] member states allowed for the relatively free movement of such goods for personal use. [[R18 (British Board of Film Classification)|R18-rated]] videos are only available in licensed sex shops, but hardcore pornographic magazines are available in shops selling newspapers and magazines. In 2008, the [[Crown Prosecution Service]] unsuccessfully prosecuted a man under the Obscene Publications Act (the ''[[R v Walker]]'' trial) for a textual story on a pornography website involving [[Girls Aloud]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/tyne/7649231.stm|title=Girls Aloud in 'murder' blog case|publisher=BBC News|date=2008-10-02|accessdate=2008-10-25}}</ref> Also that year, the [[Home Office]] introduced legislation to criminalize possession of what it has labelled [[Section 63 of the Criminal Justice and Immigration Act 2008|extreme pornography]]; these laws are now contained in sections 63 to 68 of the [[Criminal Justice and Immigration Act 2008]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.opsi.gov.uk/acts/acts2008/ukpga_20080004_en_9#pt5-pb1-l1g63|title=Criminal Justice and Immigration Act 2008|author=|date=|website=legislation.gov.uk|accessdate=8 November 2016}}</ref>

== North America ==
{{Main|Pornography in the Americas}}

=== Bahamas ===
The Bahamian penal code prohibits the production and distribution of obscene publications.<ref>{{cite web|title=Penal Code|publisher=Bahamas Government|url=http://laws.bahamas.gov.bs/cms/images/LEGISLATION/PRINCIPAL/1873/1873-0015/PenalCode_1.pdf|accessdate=30 November 2016}}</ref> Many types of pornography are prohibited in the Bahamas; however, law enforcement is relaxed and does not usually enforce the prohibition.<ref>{{cite book|title=Opposing Pornography: A look at the Anti-Pornography Movement|first=Sarah|last=Durham|publisher=Lulu.com|year=2015|isbn=9781329607644|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=MTDJCgAAQBAJ|page=61}}</ref><!--This source may be a WP mirror--> Pornography is available on Bahamian cable television<ref>{{cite news|title=Call For Ban On Porn|url=http://www.bahamaslocal.com/newsitem/39487/Call_For_Ban_On_Porn.html|date=6 January 2012|work=Bahamas Local}}</ref> and in 2014 [[ZNS-TV]] broadcast a report on the establishment of a local pornography industry in the Bahamas.<ref>{{cite news|title=Christian President Speaks Out Over Porn Industry|url=http://www.tribune242.com/news/2014/apr/25/christian-president-speaks-out-over-porn-industry/|date=25 April 2014|author=Ava Turnquest|work=The Tribune}}</ref>

=== Canada ===
{{Main|Pornography in Canada}}
The laws of Canada permit the sale of [[hardcore pornography]] to anyone over the age of eighteen. While persons below that age may have pornography in their possession, its sale to them is prohibited.

Most hardcore pornography is sold in [[Sex shop|adult stores]] or on [[Internet pornography|adult websites]].

=== Cuba ===
Pornography was illegal in Cuba during [[Fidel Castro]]'s leadership of the country, but the laws were relaxed in the 2010s.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.havanatimes.org/?p=119822|title=Pornography in Cuba, Enemy of the State|author=Frank Simon|date=7 July 2016|work=Havana Times|accessdate=30 November 2016}}</ref> However, many pornographic websites are still blocked in Cuba.{{citation needed|date=July 2018}}

=== Jamaica ===
Pornography is legal in Jamaica for adults over 18. But age verifications for buying porn or any sex-related products are relatively lax. The Jamaican government is planning to block Internet child pornography.{{citation needed|date=January 2017}}

=== Mexico ===
From early on in the 20th century [[Mexico]] was known for producing a lot of films with full female nudity and softcore pornographic scenes.{{cite needed|date=October 2014}}

=== United States ===
{{Main|Pornography in the United States}}
In the [[United States]], pornography is not unlawful at the federal level, but is subject to the [[Miller test|''Miller'' test]], which was developed in the 1973 case ''[[Miller v. California]]''.<ref>[http://caselaw.lp.findlaw.com/scripts/printer_friendly.pl?page=us/413/15.html Text of the decision and dissents], from findlaw.com</ref> The Miller test was an effort to differentiate between pornography and 'obscenity.' It has three parts:

* Whether "the average person, applying contemporary [[community standards]]", would find that the [[Work of art|work]], taken as a whole, appeals to the [[wiktionary:prurient|prurient]] interest,
* Whether the work depicts or describes, in a [[patently offensive]] way, sexual conduct specifically defined by applicable state law,
* Whether the work, taken as a whole, lacks serious [[Literature|literary]], [[art]]istic, [[Politics|political]], or [[Science|scientific]] value.<ref>This is also known as the ''(S)LAPS test''‚Äî[Serious] Literary, Artistic, Political, Scientific.</ref> The work is considered obscene only if ''all three'' conditions are satisfied. Local areas are permitted to develop their own laws on the issue, as long as they do not conflict with federal law.

Pornography is a large industry that involves major entertainment companies, which offer pornography films through cable channels and in-room movies in hotels. Pornography distribution changed radically during the 1980s, with [[VHS]] and [[cable television]] largely displacing X-rated theaters. VHS distribution, in turn, has been replaced by [[DVD]] and Internet distribution for [[niche market]]s. Pornography generates billions of dollars in sales in the United States alone. An estimated 211 new pornographic films are made every week in the United States.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/usa/story/0,12271,947880,00.html With pot and porn outstripping corn, America's black economy is flying high], ''[[The Guardian]]''</ref>

== Oceania ==
=== Australia ===
{{see also|Censorship in Australia|Pornography in Australia}}
In [[Australia]], possession of pornographic material is permitted. However, it is illegal to sell, exhibit or rent X-rated pornographic material in most [[States and territories of Australia|states of Australia]], including [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]], [[South Australia]], [[Western Australia]], [[New South Wales]], [[Tasmania]], and [[Queensland]]. In contrast, it is legal to sell, exhibit, or rent X-rated pornographic material in some [[States and territories of Australia|territories]] including the [[Northern Territory]] and the [[Australian Capital Territory]]. As the [[Constitution of Australia|Australian constitution]] prohibits states from regulating interstate commerce, the law permits the purchase of pornography from stores in either territory and also bringing it interstate. This means that the majority of Australian mail-order operations for adult material operate from the ACT.<ref>{{cite news|author=Kathy Marks|title=Canberra reborn as capital of sex|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/australasia/canberra-reborn-as-capital-of-sex-5371392.html|newspaper=The Independent|location=London|date=29 April 2000|accessdate=31 December 2015}}</ref> Despite the offenses under state laws, stores selling X-rated material are abundant in major cities, advertising openly, as these laws are rarely enforced.{{citation needed|date=February 2017}}

Ratings for the X18+ category were tightened in 2000 to ban material featuring some fetishes or which appeared to include minors.{{citation needed|date=April 2014}} In 2007 the [[Northern Territory National Emergency Response]] introduced by the [[Howard Government]] made the possession of RC and X18+ pornography an offence in some Aboriginal communities.<ref>{{cite act|title=Families, Community Services and Indigenous Affairs and Other Legislation Amendment (Northern Territory National Emergency Response and Other Measures) Bill 2007|url=http://www.aph.gov.au/binaries/library/pubs/bd/2007-08/08bd021.pdf|date=13 August 2007|number=21|type=Bill}}</ref>

=== New Zealand ===
In [[New Zealand]], pornography is generally treated in a liberal manner and very little is banned by the [[Office of Film and Literature Classification (New Zealand)|Office of Film and Literature Classification]]. However, the most extreme forms of pornography (such as [[child pornography]], [[rape]], [[incest]] and [[bestiality]]) are classified as objectionable material by the OFLC, effectively banning them.<ref>{{cite web|title=Pornography in New Zealand: do we really still need to be concerned?|url=https://www.classificationoffice.govt.nz/blog/pornography-in-nz/|date=19 January 2016|author= Deputy Chief Censor Jared Mullen|publisher=Office of Film and Literature Classification}}</ref>

=== Papua New Guinea ===
In [[Papua New Guinea]], the possession, import, export, and sale of pornography are all offenses. Control is strict. According to the government, all websites containing pornography, [[nudity]] or depictions of sex are blocked and the government has been blocking such sites since early 2009. Under the law, persons who possess, own, import, export, sell or exhibit pornography to the public are subject to arrest and trial and can face up to 6 months' imprisonment and/or a fine up to 50,000 to 100,000 [[Papua New Guinean kina]].<ref name=Durham>{{cite book|last=Durham|first=Sarah|year=2015|title=Opposing Pornography: A look at the Anti-Pornography Movement|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=MTDJCgAAQBAJ|publisher=Lulu.com|page=61|isbn=9781329607644}}</ref> In PNG, pornography is subject to legal restraints to publication on grounds of obscenity. Laws relating to pornography in Papua New Guinea are vague. The main legislation used in dealing with cases relating to pornographic nature refer back to the Chapter 262 Criminal Code of Papua New Guinea, Lukautim Pikinini Act 2009, Classification of Publication Censorship Act 1989 and the National ICT Act, 2009. Improper Use of ICT Services.<ref name=Durham/>

== South America ==
{{Main|Pornography in the Americas}}

=== Argentina ===
[[Argentina]] is emerging as another source for [[transsexual pornography]]{{reference needed|date=February 2013}}, with several titles already produced by major American companies (e.g., [[Anabolic Video]]). Argentina is also widely used to shoot pornographic clips straight for the Internet, as well as for photoshoots. Films shot in Argentina typically have the male performers wearing condoms.{{reference needed|date=February 2013}}

=== Brazil ===
In Brazil, [[pornographic film actor]]s must be 18 or older. Pornography which does not involve bestiality is legal when sold in public places. Depiction of sex with animals is legal.<ref>[http://revistagalileu.globo.com/Revista/Common/0,,EMI112289-17799,00-ALGUEM+JA+FOI+PRESO+POR+ZOOFILIA+NO+BRASIL.html Revista Galileu - ''not''√çCIAS - Algu√©m j√° foi preso por zoofilia no Brasil?<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> However, [[magazine]] and DVD covers that depict genitalia must not be visible from public view, and pornography can only be sold to people 18 or older.

=== Guyana ===
In [[Guyana]], it is illegal to sell or possess pornography. Distribution, possession, sale, and importation of pornographic magazines, DVDs, books, photographs, etc. or simply browsing for pornographic websites on the Internet can lead to a variety of punishments ranging from community service, a fine of up to 45,000 Guyana dollars, up to 2 years in prison, or [[corporal punishment]].{{citation needed|date=January 2018}}

